# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Catapult is a 65-ton fire-support BattleMech first manufactured in 2561 by Hollis Incorporated, a Terran Hegemony defense firm. Designed in anticipation of the Reunification War, the Catapult filled the role of a second-line missile platform capable of punishing enemies at extreme range while maintaining enough mobility to reposition across broken terrain. Hollis produced the chassis in substantial numbers during its initial contract, though the Hegemony deemed the design adequate rather than exceptional and declined to renew the agreement.</p><p>Produced across multiple manufacturing runs spanning the late Age of War through the Succession Wars era, the Catapult has remained one of the Inner Sphere's most recognizable heavy BattleMech silhouettes. Its distinctive pod-mounted launchers and armless profile have made it an enduring symbol of indirect fire doctrine, and the chassis has proven remarkably adaptable to a wide range of combat roles well beyond its original missile-support mission.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Catapult is primarily a fire-support platform built around a pair of Holly Long Range Missile 15-rack launchers mounted in distinctive pod-like housings flanking the cockpit. These thirty-tube launchers can begin engaging targets at ranges exceeding 600 meters, well before most opponents can effectively respond. When enemies close within the missiles' minimum effective range, four Martell medium lasers mounted below the cockpit provide adequate short-range defense capable of discouraging most light and medium 'Mechs from pressing an engagement. The design's greatest vulnerability lies in its ammunition dependency, carrying only eight reloads per launcher, which makes the Catapult heavily reliant on logistical support during extended operations.</p><p>Ten tons of Durallex Heavy armor provides respectable protection for a fire-support platform, while the Magna 260 fusion engine drives the chassis to a maximum speed of 64 kilometers per hour. Four jump jets grant a 120-meter jumping capability that allows the Catapult to keep pace with faster units across broken terrain. Early production jump jets proved prone to breakdowns that vented heat directly into the 'Mech's interior, a flaw that was addressed in later models but never fully eliminated from all operational units. The lack of arms limits close-quarters capability and leaves the design without anti-infantry weapons, reinforcing the need to maintain standoff distance whenever possible. A distinctive sideways ejection system, while generally considered safe, has been known to surprise pilots unfamiliar with the design.</p>

deployment:<p>A Periphery-produced upgrade based on the K2 configuration, the H2 replaced the twin PPCs with a single PPC and supplemented it with two medium lasers and eight twenty-tube Rocket Launcher packs. Thirteen heat sinks managed the thermal load. The result was a 'Mech capable of delivering a single devastating alpha strike of rockets followed by sustained PPC and laser fire, though the one-shot nature of the rocket launchers meant the H2's peak firepower could only be achieved once per engagement. The variant reflected Periphery ingenuity in maximizing available technology to create affordable fire-support capability.</p>

history:<p>The Catapult's operational history spans centuries of continuous service across the Inner Sphere. Hollis Incorporated was originally a Terran Hegemony company whose first production run of the Catapult predated the colonization of Corey and the formation of the Star League by nearly a decade. During the Star League era, the design served primarily with second-line and specialist formations, including mountaineering regiments that exploited its jump capability in difficult terrain. When Hollis' primary factory transitioned to BattleMaster production, limited spare parts availability caused operational numbers to gradually decline despite continued manufacturing runs that introduced various stylistic changes to the chassis profile.</p><p>The fall of the Star League marked a turning point for the Catapult. Many operational units accompanied Aleksandr Kerensky on his Exodus, while the Capellan Confederation secured the largest concentration of those remaining in the Inner Sphere. Hollis' factory on Corey briefly resumed production of new frames and spare parts, and the Draconis Combine simultaneously seized a substantial force during their capture of Dieron. The destruction of the Corey facility at the onset of the First Succession War ended renewed production and ensured the Catapult's increasing rarity throughout that devastating conflict. The design became so prized that entire invasions were launched to capture surviving examples, particularly Federated Suns campaigns against the Capellan Confederation.</p><p>The Catapult's scarcity began to reverse in 3033 when Yori 'Mech Works was contracted by the Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery to restart production on Al Na'ir, initially focusing on the CPLT-K2 variant. This renewed manufacturing capability paved the way for the CPLT-C3, the first BattleMech to mount the newly rediscovered Arrow IV artillery system. Despite a rushed development cycle that reintroduced known deficiencies, the Confederation made excellent use of C3 and Raven tandems, bringing mobile 'Mech-mounted artillery to the forefront of combined-arms doctrine. The far superior O-Bakemono might not exist if not for the C3 paving the way for 'Mech-mounted artillery.</p><p>In the years surrounding the Clan Invasion, the Capellan Confederation and Draconis Combine retained the largest active Catapult formations, though numerous Periphery realms continued to field centuries-old examples. Variant development continued through the FedCom Civil War, the Jihad, and into the Dark Age, with both Hollis Incorporated on Corey and Yori 'Mech Works on Al Na'ir and later Algedi producing new models. The Catapult's proven adaptability across fire-support, direct-fire, and artillery roles has cemented its legacy as one of the Inner Sphere's most enduring heavy BattleMech platforms.</p>

